 <datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
  <subfield code="a">
   A sound recording of songs, chants, and dance songs, some accompanied by drumming, and a discussion about aspects of Hopi religion, including dance. Recorded by Diana Cohen (Becker) in the spring of 1974 in Second Mesa, Arizona, the tape documents an informal gathering of families at the home of tribal leader Ferrell Secakuku, a songwriter, and dancer. Secakuku describes his experiences in kiva ceremonies as a kachina dancer, clown, and member of the Snake clan. He translates various phrases and explains their significance and symbolism.  Also present was Perry Honanie, Sr. who served in the United States Army during World War II as a Hopi code talker.
  </subfield>
 </datafield>
